          "body": "The chapter's central imperative arrives only after Judas departs (v. 30). *A new commandment I give to you, that you love one another, even as I have loved you* (v. 34). The commandment to love is not new in content — Leviticus 19:18 had long required love of neighbor. What is new is the **standard**: *even as I have loved you*. The cross — by now imminent — becomes the canonical measure of Christian love. And the visibility is corporate, not individual: *by this all men will know that you are My disciples, if you have love for one another* (v. 35). The world's apologetic for Christianity is the love disciples display to one another. Francis Schaeffer called this *the final apologetic* — and noted that the absence of this love grants the world the right to conclude Christ has not been sent."
